Apollon-3 // Operations Manual
1. User Interface
1.1. Status Bar
The Status Bar acts as the control center for both the Neurosity Crown EEG device
and of the main visualization system. On the right you can ﬁnd the button to connect
to your Neurosity account and to select the device (see 2.1 ) - in addition to the
visualizer control buttons: START - PAUSE/ PLAY - RESET.
1.2. Options button
This button opens a drop-down menu
that lets you select the UI color and to
activate the recording of the EEG session.
After selecting Show Recording a new
gadget pops up with a recording button, a string where you can input tags to mark
speciﬁc time-stamps - that can be called up later for playback sessions - and a close
button (X).
1.3. Output Signals EEG
The output graphs of processed EEG signals also behave like drag’n’drop icons that
can be dragged directly into the parameter panels of visualizers (see below).

2. Session setup
2.1. Neurosity Account and Crown device
Locate the DISCONNECTED button top
right of the main screen in the Status Bar.
Once pressed, the drop-down menu
where you can login, logout or load a
previous EEG session will open.
NB: if you are already connected to a Neurosity account, the button will display the
CONNECTED text. You can disconnect (logout) from here if you wish.
Enter your Neurosity account credentials
in the pop-up window.
N.B.: you can only connect to one
account at a time, but you can still
associate multiple devices to each
individual account via the Neurosity
smartphone app.

3 / 11
Once logged in, the button will display the text CONNECTED and the dropdown menu
will populate with the list of available devices tied to your account. You will see the
device name, his status (oﬄine or online) and the battery charge level in the Status
Bar.
● If the device is online and connected to the power supply, the battery icon will
also indicate the charging symbol.
● If the device is online and operational, six electrode icons will appear: the
color indicates the signal quality - from red (weak) to green (optimal).
N.B.: It is perfectly normal that during your sessions the color will occasionally
alternate from red to green very quickly as the electrical signal is subject to
continuous ﬂuctuations. As long as most of the electrodes oscillate from
yellow to green with a preponderance of the latter on average high, the quality
of the signal is to be considered as optimal.

2.2. Preprocessing parameters setting
The purpose of Preprocessing is the conditioning and the signal scaling in a range
of 0-100% through some conﬁgurable parameters.
Each panel represents one of the EEG values processed both by the device and by
the app - and shows both the input and output signal wave:
● alfa, beta, gamma, delta and theta waves;
● focus and calm;
● valence (hedonic tone of an emotion), vigilance (attention), engagement
(involvement) and workload (cognitive load).
Autoscaling OFF: Low and High represent 0 and
100% of the output respectively. When the input
signal is outside the set limits, it is cut accordingly
and the excess is blocked.
Autoscaling ON: before application, the signal is cut
(Clamp) at the speciﬁed level. Then the signal is
observed for the speciﬁed number of seconds. The
minimum and maximum in that period constitute
0-100% for the output.
Filtering: the average speciﬁed samples is calculated
- up to a maximum of 32 in increments of 8 at a time.
v.0.9
5 / 11
The input signal is ﬁxed at 4 samples per second on all wave values, therefore a higher
ﬁlter will consequently delay the output signal, but it will be more balanced and
smooth for the purpose of visualization.
2.3. Uploading EEG recording
If you select the recording of a previous EEG session (1.2. Options button) using the
item in the drop-down menu of the connection button (see 2.1. Neurosity account
connection ) a new gadget will appear at the top of the UI. This will let you play,
pause or close (eject) the recording playback - as well as jump directly to a speciﬁc
point from the "Go To" drop-down menu thanks to tags entered before.

3. “Apparitions” visualizer preparation
3.1. Parameters and input mapping
VALUE: allows you to select the value
from one of the EEG outputs
processed by the device, or
alternatively a type input Manual to
check with the relative slider 0-100%
.
If a Value is selected as EEG, the
slider will become deactivated and
grayed-out.
CURVE: select the type of mapping:
LINEAR: input signal unchanged;
REVERSE LINEAR: when the signal is lower,
the parameter is higher and vice versa;
SIGMOID: favors mapping at the extremes;
REVERSE SIGMOID: reverse the above;
GAMMA: favors a mapping to the lowest
range;
REVERSE GAMMA: reverse the above;
CENTER: favors signal mapping in the
middle of the range;
REVERSE CENTER: reverse the above.
v.0.9
7 / 11
MAPPED RANGE: The incoming 0-100%
signal is mapped to the speciﬁed range
and thus passed to the visualizer.
3.2. Brush Parameters
The various panels that contribute to the overall behavior of the brush / ink effect on
the screen.
For the most part they are of the numeric type as described in the previous point, but
with some small exceptions speciﬁed below - such as color management, background
texture management, etc…
MOVE NOISE: determines the amount of "noise" during brush movement, i.e. how
much the stroke deviates from a straight line (minimum value) to a highly random
movement (maximum value).
MOVE AMPLIFICATION: determines the speed of brush movement.
DRY RATE: determines the ink drying time.
PAINT AMOUNT: determines the amount of ink “poured”.
BACKGROUND ALPHA: determines the transparency of the texture selected in the
IMAGE panel against BACKGROUND COLOR.
INK ALPHA: determines the overall ink transparency.
MIX RATIO: determines the hardness of the edge of the brush, from sharp to soft.
PEN THICKNESS: determines the dimension of the brush.
COLOR SATURATION: determines the saturation of the brush color.
v.0.9
8 / 11
IMAGE: allows you to upload a background texture to be used as a "canvas".
N.B.: to be set at the beginning of the session! To
change (UPLOAD) or delete (CLEAR) the texture,
press the RESET in the status bar.
PEN COLOR: determines the color of the brush.
BACKGROUND COLOR: determines the color of the background.
NB: The PEN COLOR and BACKGROUND COLOR panels have speciﬁc options that
allow granular control:
Color Mode: to choose from manual RGB, HSV, LAB
and their respective automatic modes based on
Perlin Noise.
● By selecting one manual color mode, you can
set to EEG inputs: the red-green-blue color channels
/ hue-saturation-brightness / etc… ;
● By selecting one of the PERLIN modes,
values can be set manually or VARIANCE and AMPLITUDE values that control
its behavior can be associated with an EEG input.
● The M APPED RANGE controls
present a dynamic visual feedback
which varies according to the selection
and provide a useful preview for setting
the chosen values.

9 / 11
PEN DOWN: determines the “rhythm” of
the brush plotting as variation of plotting
and pauses.
In addition to the parameters Value,
Curve and Mapped Range - as described
above at 3.1 - two new entries are
featured: MODULATION and
THRESHOLD.
The Modulation allows you to toggle
between None (manual), Triangle (regular
rhythm) and Perlin (random). The
Threshold value determines the rhythm
of raise / lower of the brush on the
screen (i.e Invisible or visible) relative to
the Modulation together with the input Value.
EXAMPLES:
● Modulation > NONE - Threshold > 50% - Value > Manual > 75%
will determine a continuous plotting without interruptions.
● Modulation > NONE - Threshold > 50% - Value > FOCUS
will determine an alternate plotting based on the FOCUS value.
● Modulation > TRIANGLE - Threshold > 80% - Value > Manual > 85%
will determine a regular alternate plotting like a dotted line.

3.3. Visualizer options
A visualizer can present speciﬁc options accessible via the Options button located at
the top right above parameter panels
along with two buttons for save and
load the presets for brush settings. In
the speciﬁc case of the "Apparitions” visualizer there are three options and they all
relate to the behavior of the brush:
PEN COLOR: determines whether the brush color should
vary continuously based on the input values or if it should be
kept constant as long as the brush is active and vary only
when it is hidden according to the threshold set in the PEN
DOWN panel.
PEN DOWN POSITION: determines whether the brush
position should be sequential in respect to the last visible
stroke (always dependent on PEN DOWN) or move randomly
on the screen at each pen up/down.
MOVEMENT MAPPING: determines whether the brush
movement must be sequential and "inﬁnite” or if it can go
beyond the screen borders just to then reappear on the
opposite side - or if it has to bounce on the screen edges.
